Hello Saveetha, Fenil, 

Thank you for your time on a meeting today. 
Here is a recap of today`s meeting for your records:

Using a PowerShell script that is attached to this email we tested connection to IPC$ share of the Target NetApp hosts from Proxy servers. 
The test was performed using credentials of the "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" account - because this is the account that the FSAA scans are configured to use. 

First, we performed test for the FRBBI site for which FSAA scan is failing, where Proxy is FRBBI-IMS02 and target NetApp is BBI01-NS012. 
Using "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" account the PowerShell script could not connect to \BBI01-NS012IPC$ share:


The same issue is happening during FSAA scan - the "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" account is used from FRBBI-IMS02 proxy.
But the scan is failing with "Cannot connect to server with any selected protocol" because FRBBI-IMS02 proxy cannot connect to IPC$ share of the BBI01-NS012 target using "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp". 

We also performed the same test but for proxy servers and target NetApp hosts for which the FSAA scan is successful.
Using PowerShell script and "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" account we successfully connected to IPC$ share of the target NetApp hosts for which scan runs successfully:
DEIDUICS-OFS012:


ACM01-NS012:


Results of these tests performed with script correlate with results of the FSAA scans in StealthAudit.
As such, the script can be used by your Networking team as a valid tool for troubleshooting of the issue. 

According to information we collected so far using "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" account from some proxy servers works, but when the same account is used from other proxy servers - then FSAA scan fails (such as in case of FRBBI-IMS02 proxy for example). 
As we agreed, you will contact Networking team and provide this PowerShell Script to them as well as results of the tests we performed today. 

 

To continue, we also discussed this error message:
Failed to copy StealthAUDIT.lic file to base FSAA folder: Access is denied"

In previous tickets this issue was known to be resolved after restart of the StealthAudit console. As such, please, restart the StealthAudit console, then retry the FSAA scan that was failing with this error and let me know results. 
If the issue is still taking place - I will open a separate ticket for it to continue investigation. 

 

I am looking forward to hearing back from you!

Best regards,
Artem Naskal
Technical Support Engineer EMEA

Hello Saveetha, Fenil, 

Thank you very much for your time on a meeting today.
I am pleased to say that we made progress today because we isolated the issue to the "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" account.

Here is a recap of what we did today:

Allow me to describe an issue once more to make sure we cover all the details.
Currently you are experiencing an issue with FSAA permission scans for many NetApp hosts from GLOBAL and NHY domains. 
Each of the target NetApp host mentioned has their own corresponding Proxy server. 

Each of these proxy servers use the same connection profile:
GLOBAL NETAPP

This connection profile consists of these two service accounts:
GLOBALs-stealthnetapp (Active Directory Account) - this account is used to connect to target NetApp host from Proxy server.
NHYs01305proxy (StealthAudit task (Domain)) - this account is used to connect to Proxy from Stealth Audit server using Secure RPC.

On today`s remote session we checked required network ports and WMI connection between StealthAudit server and Proxy servers.
Ports 445 and 135 are opened and WMI connection test was successful as well.

Also, we confirmed that connection between StealthAudit server and Proxy servers using "NHYs01305proxy" account for "Secure RPC" works successfully.
Both Job and FSAA applet logs indicate that connection from Stealth Audit to Proxy can be successfully established when "NHYs01305proxy" account is used and "Use secure RPC connection" checkbox is enabled in Job Query settings.

However, issue appears when Proxy service tries to connect to target NetApp host using "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" account to enumerate NetApp`s shares.
As such, in order to resolve this issue, you need to find out why "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" account leads to the error "Failed to connect to \TargetNetAppHostIPC$" when this account is used from the Proxy servers in question to connect to NetApp target hosts affected by the issue.

We agreed that you will contact Network and NetApp teams to clarify why "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" account is failing to connect to target NetApp hosts from corresponding Proxy servers to access/enumerate available shares. 
In the meantime, we will clarify which isolation test can display issue with "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" account outside of StealthAudit.  

Please, let me know once you have news from your side. 
And I will reach out to you as soon as I have an update. 

Looking forward to hearing back from you. 
Thank you! 

Best regards,
Artem Naskal
Technical Support Engineer EMEA

Hello Saveetha, Fenil, 

Thank you very much for your time on a meeting today.
I am pleased to say that we made progress today because we isolated the issue to the "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" account.

Here is a recap of what we did today:

Allow me to describe an issue once more to make sure we cover all the details.
Currently you are experiencing an issue with FSAA permission scans for many NetApp hosts from GLOBAL and NHY domains. 
Each of the target NetApp host mentioned has their own corresponding Proxy server. 

Each of these proxy servers use the same connection profile:
GLOBAL NETAPP

This connection profile consists of these two service accounts:
GLOBALs-stealthnetapp (Active Directory Account) - this account is used to connect to target NetApp host from Proxy server.
NHYs01305proxy (StealthAudit task (Domain)) - this account is used to connect to Proxy from Stealth Audit server using Secure RPC.

On today`s remote session we checked required network ports and WMI connection between StealthAudit server and Proxy servers.
Ports 445 and 135 are opened and WMI connection test was successful as well.

Also, we confirmed that connection between StealthAudit server and Proxy servers using "NHYs01305proxy" account for "Secure RPC" works successfully.
Both Job and FSAA applet logs indicate that connection from Stealth Audit to Proxy can be successfully established when "NHYs01305proxy" account is used and "Use secure RPC connection" checkbox is enabled in Job Query settings.

However, issue appears when Proxy service tries to connect to target NetApp host using "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" account to enumerate NetApp`s shares.
As such, in order to resolve this issue, you need to find out why "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" account leads to the error "Failed to connect to \TargetNetAppHostIPC$" when this account is used from the Proxy servers in question to connect to NetApp target hosts affected by the issue.

We agreed that you will contact Network and NetApp teams to clarify why "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" account is failing to connect to target NetApp hosts from corresponding Proxy servers to access/enumerate available shares. 
In the meantime, we will clarify which isolation test can display issue with "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" account outside of StealthAudit.  

Please, let me know once you have news from your side. 
And I will reach out to you as soon as I have an update. 

Looking forward to hearing back from you. 
Thank you!

Hello Saveetha, Fenil,

Thank you very much for your time on a meeting today.
I am pleased to say that we made progress today because we isolated the issue to the "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" account.

Here is a recap of what we did today:

Allow me to describe an issue once more to make sure we cover all the details.
Currently you are experiencing an issue with FSAA permission scans for many NetApp hosts from GLOBAL and NHY domains.
Each of the target NetApp host mentioned has their own corresponding Proxy server.

Each of these proxy servers use the same connection profile:
GLOBAL NETAPP

This connection profile consists of these two service accounts:
GLOBALs-stealthnetapp (Active Directory Account) - this account is used to connect to target NetApp host from Proxy server.
NHYs01305proxy (StealthAudit task (Domain)) - this account is used to connect to Proxy from Stealth Audit server using Secure RPC.

On today`s remote session we checked required network ports and WMI connection between StealthAudit server and Proxy servers.
Ports 445 and 135 are opened and WMI connection test was successful as well.

Also, we confirmed that connection between StealthAudit server and Proxy servers using "NHYs01305proxy" account for "Secure RPC" works successfully.
Both Job and FSAA applet logs indicate that connection from Stealth Audit to Proxy can be successfully established when "NHYs01305proxy" account is used and "Use secure RPC connection" checkbox is enabled in Job Query settings.

However, issue appears when Proxy service tries to connect to target NetApp host using "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" account to enumerate NetApp`s shares.
As such, in order to resolve this issue, you need to find out why "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" account leads to the error "Failed to connect to \TargetNetAppHostIPC$<file://TargetNetAppHost/IPC$>" when this account is used from the Proxy servers in question to connect to NetApp target hosts affected by the issue.

We agreed that you will contact Network and NetApp teams to clarify why "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" account is failing to connect to target NetApp hosts from corresponding Proxy servers to access/enumerate available shares.
In the meantime, we will clarify which isolation test can display issue with "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" account outside of StealthAudit.

Please, let me know once you have news from your side.
And I will reach out to you as soon as I have an update.

Looking forward to hearing back from you.
Thank you!

TextBody:
Hello Saveetha, 

Thank you for sharing this information with us. 

I have consulted with my team and would like to suggest you additional troubleshooting steps. 
These tests will allow you to check if NetAPP FSAA Scan port requirements are met or not:

1. In FSAA System Scan query settings check the Scan Settings > NetApp communication security settings:


2. Depending on what is set in "NetApp communication security settings" - contact your networking team and ask them to check either port 443 (for HTTPS) or port 80 (for HTTP) between NEA server and target NetAPP host affected by the issue at hand.

3. Next, perform Test-NetConnection command check from IMS02 Proxy servers from which scan is failing to the NetAPP host affected by the issue:
Test-NetConnection -ComputerName <hostname> -Port 445

This command must be run from Proxy server, which are IMS02 servers in your environment.
<hostname> must be the hostname of the target NetAPP for which scan is failing.

If "Test-NetConnection -ComputerName <hostname> -Port 445" that is executed on IMS02 Proxy is failing - then contact your networking team and ask them to allow port 445 (for SMB connection) between StealthAudit FSAA Proxy Server to NetAPP hosts. 


Best regards,
Artem Naskal
Technical Support Engineer EMEA

Hello Saveetha,

Thank you for sharing this information with us.

I have consulted with my team and would like to suggest you additional troubleshooting steps.
These tests will allow you to check if NetAPP FSAA Scan port requirements are met or not:

1. In FSAA System Scan query settings check the Scan Settings > NetApp communication security settings:
[Image_2025-03-12_20-36-25.png]

2. Depending on what is set in "NetApp communication security settings" - contact your networking team and ask them to check either port 443 (for HTTPS) or port 80 (for HTTP) between NEA server and target NetAPP host affected by the issue at hand.

3. Next, perform Test-NetConnection command check from IMS02 Proxy servers from which scan is failing to the NetAPP host affected by the issue:
Test-NetConnection -ComputerName <hostname> -Port 445

This command must be run from Proxy server, which are IMS02 servers in your environment.
<hostname> must be the hostname of the target NetAPP for which scan is failing.

If "Test-NetConnection -ComputerName <hostname> -Port 445" that is executed on IMS02 Proxy is failing - then contact your networking team and ask them to allow port 445 (for SMB connection) between StealthAudit FSAA Proxy Server to NetAPP hosts.

GLOBAL NETAPP

GLOBALs-stealthnetapp (Active Directory Account) - this account is used to connect to target NetApp host from Proxy server.
NHYs01305proxy (StealthAudit task (Domain)) - this account is used to connect to Proxy from Stealth Audit server using Secure RPC.

Hello Saveetha, Thank you for sharing this information with us. I have consulted with my team and would like to suggest you additional troubleshooting steps. These tests will allow you to check if NetAPP FSAA Scan port requirements are met or

 

Hello Saveetha, 

Thank you for sharing this information with us. 

I have consulted with my team and would like to suggest you additional troubleshooting steps. 
These tests will allow you to check if NetAPP FSAA Scan port requirements are met or not:

1. In FSAA System Scan query settings check the Scan Settings > NetApp communication security settings:


2. Depending on what is set in "NetApp communication security settings" - contact your networking team and ask them to check either port 443 (for HTTPS) or port 80 (for HTTP) between NEA server and target NetAPP host affected by the issue at hand.

3. Next, perform Test-NetConnection command check from IMS02 Proxy  servers from which scan is failing to the NetAPP host affected by the issue:
Test-NetConnection -ComputerName <hostname> -Port 445

This command must be run from Proxy server, which are IMS02 servers in your environment.
<hostname> must be the hostname of the target NetAPP for which scan is failing.

If "Test-NetConnection -ComputerName <hostname> -Port 445" that is executed on IMS02 Proxy is failing - then contact your networking team and ask them to allow port 445 (for SMB connection) between StealthAudit FSAA Proxy Server to NetAPP hosts. 


Best regards,
Artem Naskal

Currently you are experiencing an issue with FSAA permission scans for many NetApp hosts from GLOBAL and NHY domains. 
Each of the target NetApp host mentioned has their own corresponding Proxy server. 

Each of these proxy servers use the same connection profile:
GLOBAL NETAPP

This connection profile consists of these two service accounts:
GLOBALs-stealthnetapp (Active Directory Account) - this account is used to connect to target NetApp host from Proxy server.
NHYs01305proxy (StealthAudit task (Domain)) - this account is used to connect to Proxy from Stealth Audit server using Secure RPC.

On today`s remote session we checked required network ports and WMI connection between StealthAudit server and Proxy servers.
Ports 445 and 135 are opened and WMI connection test was successful as well.

Also, we confirmed that connection between StealthAudit server and Proxy servers using "NHYs01305proxy" account for "Secure RPC" works successfully.
Both Job and FSAA applet logs indicate that connection from Stealth Audit to Proxy can be successfully established when "NHYs01305proxy" account is used and "Use secure RPC connection" checkbox is enabled in Job Query settings.

However, issue appears when Proxy service tries to connect to target NetApp host using "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" account to enumerate NetApp`s shares.
As such, in order to resolve this issue, you need to find out why "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" account leads to the error "Failed to connect to \TargetNetAppHostIPC$" when this account is used from the Proxy servers in question to connect to NetApp target hosts affected by the issue.

We agreed that you will contact Network and NetApp teams to clarify why "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" account is failing to connect to target NetApp hosts from corresponding Proxy servers to access/enumerate available shares. 
In the meantime, we will clarify which isolation test can display issue with "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" account outside of StealthAudit.

TextBody: Hi Saveetha, Thank you for getting back to us with an update. This ticket is for troubleshooting FSAA scan error when using "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" to access NetAPP hosts shares. Last time we suggested to either use a PowerShell script that performs a "netuse" command with "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" account to one of the NetAPP shares. Or perform these additional tests to see if network requirements are met: 1. In FSAA System Scan query settings check the Scan Settings > NetApp communication security settings: 2. Depending on what is set in "NetApp communication security settings" - contact your networking team and ask them to check either port 443 (for HTTPS) or port 80 (for HTTP) between NEA server and target NetAPP host affected by the issue at hand. 3. Next, perform Test-NetConnection command check from IMS02 Proxy servers from which scan is failing to the NetAPP host affected by the issue: Test-NetConnection -ComputerName -Port 445 This command must be run from Proxy server, which are IMS02 servers in your environment. must be the hostname of the target NetAPP for which scan is failing. If "Test-NetConnection -ComputerName -Port 445" that is executed on IMS02 Proxy is failing - then contact your networking team and ask them to allow port 445 (for SMB connection) between StealthAudit FSAA Proxy Server to NetAPP hosts. Could you let me know, do you have status for that? Have you tried steps above with your Networking team? TextBody: ref:_00D7091pB._500Q000Lb1Ne:ref Hello Artem, We have followed the steps outlined, and the issue seems to be related to NAME RESOLUTION. When using the FQDN with port 445, the test is successful. However, when using only the NetApp name (without the FQDN), the test fails. TextBody: Hi Saveetha, Thank you for the update and for clarifying all these details. The Host name resolution and Test-NetConnection on port 445 only works if you are using FQDN for the problematic NetApp hosts. If you are looking to resolve this and make problematic NetAPP host available with Hostname only - then you need to contact your NetAPP and networking team who are responsible for this kind of configuration. Contact them and provide them with information and screenshot you provided to us in the last email - this will be enough for them to start investigation and resolve this. I also must point out, that even if you make problematic NetAPP host available via Hostname only - you still need to make sure that "netapp IPC$ check" PowerShell script runs successfully from the problematic Proxy using "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" user account. As such, I would highly recommend contacting your Networking team and team responsible for configuring NetAPP hosts and ask them to assist you with resolving both issues: NetAPP hostname resolution without FQDN And making sure "netapp IPC$ check" PowerShell script runs successfully from the problematic Proxy using "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" user account I have attached PowerShell script to this email. TextBody: Hi Saveetha, The following was provided from our side as a list of requirements that should be met in your environment for successful NetAPP host FSAA scan: 1. First of all, we suggested using a PowerShell script that performs a "netuse" command with "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" account to one of the NetAPP shares. You can find the script attached to this email. Script must be run from the Proxy server and target NetAPP host. Script must also use "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" account as this is the account that is configured in Netwrix Enterprise Auditor. To target different NetAPP hosts you need to modify the following variables inside the script: $NetAppHost = "10.62.3.153" $SharePath = "\$NetAppHostIPC$" To use "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" account its credentials must be provided to this variable inside the script: $Accounts = @( @{ Username = "username"; Password = "Password" } @{ Username = "domainusername"; Password = "Password" } ) If script is not producing successful results - this means that you must engage your NetAPP team and possibly NetAPP support to resolve this issue. Script must run successfully to ensure successful FSAA Scan against NetAPP hosts. Alternatively, these additional tests were suggested to see if network requirements are met: 2. In FSAA System Scan query settings check the Scan Settings > NetApp communication security settings: 3. Depending on what is set in "NetApp communication security settings" - contact your networking team and ask them to check either port 443 (for HTTPS) or port 80 (for HTTP) between NEA server and target NetAPP host affected by the issue at hand. 4. Next, perform Test-NetConnection command check from IMS02 Proxy servers from which scan is failing to the NetAPP host affected by the issue: Test-NetConnection -ComputerName -Port 445 This command must be run from Proxy server, which are IMS02 servers in your environment. must be the hostname of the target NetAPP for which scan is failing. If "Test-NetConnection -ComputerName -Port 445" that is executed on IMS02 Proxy is failing - then contact your networking team and ask them to allow port 445 (for SMB connection) between StealthAudit FSAA Proxy Server to NetAPP hosts. Best regards, Artem Naskal Technical Support Engineer EMEA ____________________ _________ Cybersecurity That Works for You 6160 Warren Parkway, Suite 100, Frisco, TX 75034 www.netwrix.com --------------- Original Message --------------- From: SAVEETHA ANESH [saveetha.a@kyndryl.com] Sent: 4/3/2025 7:49 PM To: techsupport@netwrix.com Cc: hydro-india-windows@kyndryl.com; nagendra.prasad1@kyndryl.com; ramesh.r3@kyndryl.com; fenilkumar.s@kyndryl.com Subject: RE: Netwrix Support Ticket #435045 - - 00435045 - Error during processing: Cannot connect to server with any selected protocol" [ ref:!00D70091pB.!500Qk0Lb1Ne:ref ] ref:_00D7091pB._500Q000Lb1Ne:ref Hello Artem, WORKING NETAPP: Source : NLANLPV-IMS02 Destination: NLANLICS-OFS012 Access has been granted for both the account "NHYs01305proxy" and "Globals-stealthnetapp". Report Suspicious Hi Saveetha, Thank you for the update and for clarifying all these details. The Host name resolution and Test-NetConnection on port 445 only works if you are using FQDN for the problematic NetApp hosts. If you are looking to resolve this and make problematic NetAPP host available with Hostname only - then you need to contact your NetAPP and networking team who are responsible for this kind of configuration. Contact them and provide them with information and screenshot you provided to us in the last email - this will be enough for them to start investigation and resolve this. I also must point out, that even if you make problematic NetAPP host available via Hostname only - you still need to make sure that "netapp IPC$ check" PowerShell script runs successfully from the problematic Proxy using "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" user account. As such, I would highly recommend contacting your Networking team and team responsible for configuring NetAPP hosts and ask them to assist you with resolving both issues: NetAPP hostname resolution without FQDN And making sure "netapp IPC$ check" PowerShell script runs successfully from the problematic Proxy using "GLOBALs-stealthnetapp" user account I have attached PowerShell script to this email. Next, perform Test-NetConnection command check from IMS02 Proxy servers from which scan is failing to the NetAPP host affected by the issue: Test-NetConnection -ComputerName -Port 445 This command must be run from Proxy server, which are IMS02 servers in your environment. must be the hostname of the target NetAPP for which scan is failing. TextBody: Hi Saveetha, Thank you for the prompt reply. I am happy to hear that this resolved the issue for you! This is great news. The following is a recap of the ticket for your records: Netwrix Access Analyzer (formerly known as Enterprise Auditor) FSAA scans could not start against some NetAPP hosts in NHY and Global domain. After performing multiple troubleshooting steps and tests it was found that the following Test-NetConnection command is failing against NetAPP hosts with issue when only hostname is used: Test-NetConnection -ComputerName -Port 445 Command could run successfully for other NetAPP hosts when only hostname is used, but for those NetAPP hosts that were having issues in Netwrix Access Analyzer (Enterprise Auditor) - the same command was failing when only target host name is used. After adding needed DNS server records issue was resolved for previously failing NetAPP hosts. Following this email, you will receive an automated confirmation that the case is closed, along with the ability to re-open the case if any related errors return. In addition, you will also receive a separate email with a survey where you can let us know how we did. Feel free to leave any feedback via the survey link!
